WEBVTT

00:02.936 --> 00:05.973
DR. GLASSMAN: Shaun,
you need to make a decision.

00:09.177 --> 00:11.079
Shaun, please.
Your mom's been calling.

00:11.112 --> 00:12.546
Your father wants
to talk to you.

00:16.317 --> 00:18.719
Say something, will you?
Say anything.

00:24.725 --> 00:27.027
I know he wasn't
a good father,

00:27.061 --> 00:29.497
but he's the only father
you've got.

00:29.530 --> 00:32.466
If ever there was something
you wanted to say to him,

00:32.500 --> 00:33.901
now's the time.

00:37.805 --> 00:40.808
I have nothing
to say to him.

00:41.742 --> 00:43.211
Okay.

00:43.244 --> 00:48.149
But if he wants to say
something to me
before he dies,

00:48.182 --> 00:49.183
I'll listen.

00:51.152 --> 00:52.620
Okay.

00:52.653 --> 00:54.622
Can you come with me?
Yeah, of course.

00:54.655 --> 00:56.056
Can I bring a friend?

00:56.090 --> 00:57.558
I don't think
that's a good idea.

00:57.591 --> 01:00.561
I want to bring a friend.

01:00.594 --> 01:02.730
Shaun, how... How long
have you been dating Carly?

01:02.763 --> 01:04.998
I don't want
to bring Carly.

01:05.032 --> 01:06.367
I want to bring Lea.

01:13.607 --> 01:16.110
(UPBEAT MUSIC PLAYS ON STEREO)

01:19.180 --> 01:20.414
Morning.

01:21.349 --> 01:22.650
Never seen you here
before.

01:22.683 --> 01:24.685
Yeah, I just joined.

01:24.718 --> 01:26.053
I'm not really
a gym person,

01:26.086 --> 01:28.889
but I, uh, thought
I'd try something new.

01:28.922 --> 01:30.424
It's a great way
to clear your head.

01:31.525 --> 01:32.726
Yeah. Um...

01:33.461 --> 01:34.928
About last night.

01:34.962 --> 01:36.730
In the stairwell.

01:36.764 --> 01:37.765
Thanks.

01:38.632 --> 01:39.633
No problem.

01:41.068 --> 01:43.237
I know the boss
isn't always the person
you want to talk to,

01:43.271 --> 01:44.938
but if you ever do...

01:44.972 --> 01:47.741
Thanks again.
But I'm fine.
Really.

01:49.410 --> 01:51.412
(METAL CLANKS)

01:51.445 --> 01:53.147
(MAN EXHALES SHARPLY)
Is that guy serious?

01:53.181 --> 01:55.349
(GRUNTS)
That's it.
That's it.

01:55.383 --> 01:57.451
I'm gonna say yes,
since that's Art Kalman.

01:58.752 --> 02:00.454
Raiders'
offensive tackle.

02:01.589 --> 02:02.890
(GRUNTING)

02:02.923 --> 02:04.858
That's like 800 pounds.

02:04.892 --> 02:06.394
It's the NFL.

02:06.427 --> 02:07.461
No pain, no paycheck.

02:07.495 --> 02:09.563
MAN: Come on!
Awesome, man.
We got you.

02:09.597 --> 02:10.631
One more.

02:10.664 --> 02:11.732
Naw, man.
Come on,
you're good.

02:11.765 --> 02:13.467
One...more!

02:13.501 --> 02:15.403
(WEIGHTS CLINK)

02:15.436 --> 02:16.904
Push, push, push!

02:16.937 --> 02:18.772
Push!
(GRUNTING)

02:21.442 --> 02:22.976
(BONE CRACKS)
Aah!

02:23.010 --> 02:24.478
(METAL CLANGS)
(GROANS, SCREAMS)

02:24.512 --> 02:26.079
TRAINER: Are you okay?
(PANTING)

02:26.113 --> 02:27.415
Can you hear me?
Don't move.

02:27.448 --> 02:28.849
I'm a doctor.
Where's it hurt?

02:29.983 --> 02:31.652
It doesn't, but...
I can't move.

02:32.253 --> 02:33.254
Call 911.

02:34.788 --> 02:36.123
I can't feel my legs!

02:36.156 --> 02:37.225
Listen to me, Art.

02:37.258 --> 02:38.459
You need to hold still.

02:38.492 --> 02:40.461
I'm gonna take
good care of you.
I can't feel my legs!

02:40.494 --> 02:43.197
(THEME MUSIC PLAYING)

03:01.114 --> 03:02.650
(SIGHS)

03:02.683 --> 03:04.518
You know,
you don't have to go
if you don't want to.

03:04.552 --> 03:05.653
I can handle it.

03:05.686 --> 03:07.588
I don't want to go.

03:07.621 --> 03:09.757
I obviously have
no wisdom to offer...

03:09.790 --> 03:11.659
My own family's a disaster.

03:11.692 --> 03:13.694
And things are
crazy-busy
at work now.

03:14.027 --> 03:15.663
Okay.

03:15.696 --> 03:17.365
But he's my best friend,

03:17.398 --> 03:18.766
and he seems to need
my support,

03:18.799 --> 03:21.635
so there's no way
I'm gonna say no.

03:21.669 --> 03:24.204
Well, don't force
yourself to go
if you don't want to.

03:24.238 --> 03:25.439
Sounds like
you don't want me to go.

03:25.473 --> 03:27.308
It's just that it's...

03:27.341 --> 03:29.277
It's gonna be intense,
it's gonna be emotional.

03:29.310 --> 03:30.478
Really?

03:30.511 --> 03:32.079
I thought going home
to visit the parents

03:32.112 --> 03:34.648
who abused and abandoned him
would be a fun family reunion.

03:34.682 --> 03:35.983
Why are you getting
defensive?

03:36.016 --> 03:37.117
Why do you have to be
controlling?

03:37.150 --> 03:38.819
How am I controlling?
Hmm.

03:38.852 --> 03:39.887
I'm just ask...
I'm ready to go.

03:42.390 --> 03:45.393
We have to be at
the airport 90 minutes
prior to our flight.

03:47.861 --> 03:50.063
**

03:53.701 --> 03:55.836
Can you believe
the size of this guy?

03:55.869 --> 03:57.871
DR. PARK: Exactly why
I don't watch football.

03:57.905 --> 04:00.073
Size is more important
than talent or skill.

04:00.107 --> 04:01.675
I'm gonna guess
you never played.

04:02.876 --> 04:05.879
Half the players
are morbidly obese.

04:05.913 --> 04:07.415
DR. REZNICK: Yet they
can still run 4.9 forties

04:07.448 --> 04:09.617
and have
36-inch verticals.

04:09.650 --> 04:11.585
It doesn't matter
what kind of body
you're born with.

04:11.619 --> 04:12.853
No one makes it
to the top

04:12.886 --> 04:14.221
unless they're
incredibly talented

04:14.254 --> 04:16.023
and they worked
their ass off.

04:16.056 --> 04:17.725
It's just stupid.

04:17.758 --> 04:20.193
Jocks get paid millions
and get treated like royalty,

04:20.227 --> 04:23.331
whereas people
who do jobs that
actually matter...

04:23.364 --> 04:25.533
Teachers, cops,
doctors...

04:25.566 --> 04:27.435
(SCOFFS) We can barely pay
our student loans.

04:27.468 --> 04:29.670
Someone woke up
on the wrong side
of the bed.

04:29.703 --> 04:31.171
I'm gonna guess
someone else's.

04:32.973 --> 04:34.342
I'm not doing
that anymore.

04:36.276 --> 04:37.745
Just like that?

04:37.778 --> 04:38.979
Just like that.

04:40.314 --> 04:43.116
**

04:43.150 --> 04:45.052
(MONITOR BEEPS)
(EXHALES SHARPLY)

04:45.085 --> 04:46.754
This is bad.

04:46.787 --> 04:50.223
Burst and facet fractures...
T3 and 4.

04:50.257 --> 04:53.026
Retropulsion
of bony fragments
in the spinal canal.

04:53.060 --> 04:54.094
But look here.

04:54.127 --> 04:56.664
There's no transectional
bruising in his spinal cord.

04:59.299 --> 05:01.134
SHAUN: We're in
boarding group A, right?

05:01.168 --> 05:02.736
Boarding group A,

05:02.770 --> 05:04.705
no emergency exit row,

05:04.738 --> 05:05.939
right side of the plane.

05:09.009 --> 05:10.978
Have you spoken
to Carly?

05:11.011 --> 05:12.946
Not since last night.

05:12.980 --> 05:14.415
Well, don't you think
you should call her,

05:14.448 --> 05:17.618
let her know where
you're going and why
and with whom?

05:20.153 --> 05:22.823
She won't worry.

05:22.856 --> 05:24.425
She knows
I don't like my dad,

05:24.458 --> 05:25.926
so I won't be sad
when he dies.

05:25.959 --> 05:27.828
Shaun...

05:27.861 --> 05:29.963
Call her
and let her know

05:29.997 --> 05:31.465
that you're...
You're gonna miss her.

05:31.499 --> 05:33.967
She must know
I'll miss her.

05:34.001 --> 05:35.603
Tell her anyway.

05:35.636 --> 05:37.170
(TRUNK LID CLOSES)
You know it must be
good advice

05:37.204 --> 05:38.606
if he and I
actually agree.

05:47.014 --> 05:48.148
If we can stabilize
the fractures

05:48.181 --> 05:49.349
and decompress
the cord,

05:49.383 --> 05:50.984
we should be able to
reverse the paralysis.

05:51.018 --> 05:52.686
Fantastic. We should
start a preoperative

05:52.720 --> 05:53.787
Riluzole regimen.

05:53.821 --> 05:54.855
No.

05:56.189 --> 05:58.325
There's an experimental
hypothermia treatment

05:58.358 --> 06:00.260
shown to reduce cord edema
and cell death

06:00.293 --> 06:01.395
when done prior
to surgery.

06:03.464 --> 06:07.100
It's also shown a high rate
of bradycardia
and arrhythmias,

06:07.134 --> 06:09.637
which is the last thing I want
to deal with during surgery.

06:09.670 --> 06:12.473
There's an infusion protocol
we can follow
to reduce that risk.

06:12.506 --> 06:14.107
The faster we reduce
the inflammation...

06:14.141 --> 06:15.543
Thank you,
I appreciate your input,

06:15.576 --> 06:16.877
but as Art's surgeon...

06:16.910 --> 06:18.646
She's right.

06:18.679 --> 06:20.548
And what makes you think
you're doing the surgery?

06:20.581 --> 06:23.016
Dr. Melendez, I appreciate
all you've done.

06:23.050 --> 06:25.653
But now that he's stable,
my staff will take over.

06:25.686 --> 06:27.988
Well, actually,
that's not your call.

06:28.021 --> 06:29.022
Or mine.

06:30.824 --> 06:35.463
You're a pro athlete
with a pro athlete's body.

06:35.496 --> 06:37.798
And you need a surgeon
who understands

06:37.831 --> 06:41.301
that this is not just
about making sure
you can walk again.

06:41.334 --> 06:44.672
It's about making sure
you can run, block,

06:44.705 --> 06:46.807
so you can get back out
on that field

06:46.840 --> 06:48.075
and play at the top
of your game.

06:48.676 --> 06:50.478
This is what I do.

06:50.511 --> 06:52.813
Sure, you do knees,
you do shoulders.

06:52.846 --> 06:54.748
Have you ever
done anything
like this before?

06:54.782 --> 06:56.684
Robert Stokes,
last year.

06:56.717 --> 06:58.686
Donny Lund
a few years before that.

06:58.719 --> 07:00.888
Both players had
similar spinal fractures.

07:01.755 --> 07:03.090
Actually, not that similar.

07:05.092 --> 07:07.761
This is more like what
I see in high-speed
motorcycle accidents.

07:07.795 --> 07:09.863
And unfortunately,
I've seen a lot of those.

07:09.897 --> 07:13.200
Not one or two
every few years,
but 20 to 30 every year.

07:14.301 --> 07:15.302
That's what I do.

07:21.274 --> 07:23.477
(SIGHS)

07:24.377 --> 07:25.813
This is gonna be
awesome.

07:36.123 --> 07:37.124
Have you got
something to say?

07:38.425 --> 07:40.360
I get you want to deal
with stuff on your own,

07:40.393 --> 07:42.796
for people to mind
their own business.

07:42.830 --> 07:45.699
But whatever pressure
you've been feeling
is still here.

07:45.733 --> 07:48.401
If you don't seek help
or rely on other people,

07:49.169 --> 07:50.270
you will fail.

07:53.106 --> 07:54.575
Thank you.

07:54.608 --> 07:56.309
Should we get
back to work now?

07:56.343 --> 07:58.445
**

08:00.447 --> 08:01.615
WOMAN: (ON PA)
Ladies and gentlemen,

08:01.649 --> 08:03.450
welcome to Cheyenne
Regional Airport.

08:03.483 --> 08:05.586
**

08:18.031 --> 08:19.700
(BRAKES SQUEAK)

08:21.101 --> 08:23.003
(KEYS JINGLE,
ENGINE SHUTS OFF)

08:23.036 --> 08:24.938
(BIRDS CHIRPING)

08:29.376 --> 08:31.178
I changed my mind.

08:31.211 --> 08:34.281
I don't want to hear
what he has to say.

08:34.314 --> 08:36.149
I think you do want to hear
what he has to say.

08:36.183 --> 08:37.818
No. No.

08:37.851 --> 08:40.087
LEA: Okay...
I-I don't want to be here.

08:40.120 --> 08:42.656
Shaun...
Okay, why don't we just sit
in the car for a while?

08:42.690 --> 08:44.057
There's no rush.

08:46.827 --> 08:47.861
Okay.

08:52.132 --> 08:54.635
**

09:04.712 --> 09:05.713
I want to go.

09:07.681 --> 09:09.349
Now.

09:09.382 --> 09:11.318
Shaun,
take a deep breath.
No, thank you.

09:11.351 --> 09:12.820
I don't want
to take a breath.

09:12.853 --> 09:15.022
Shaun, just...
No, I want to go!

09:15.055 --> 09:16.890
I want to go.
DR. GLASSMAN: Okay.

09:16.924 --> 09:18.726
I want to go now!
Okay.

09:18.759 --> 09:20.460
Go now! Please!
Okay, okay, okay.
Okay. Okay.

09:20.493 --> 09:21.662
Okay. Okay.
Please.

09:21.695 --> 09:22.930
(ENGINE STARTS)
Here we go.

09:22.963 --> 09:24.497
Please, okay, go now.
We're going back
to the hotel.

09:24.531 --> 09:25.565
I'm sorry.
Go now!

09:25.599 --> 09:26.834
We'll settle in
at the hotel...
Go now!

09:26.867 --> 09:28.035
We're going.
It's gonna be okay.

09:28.068 --> 09:29.603
We're going.
Go now, please!

09:29.637 --> 09:31.304
We'll settle in
at the hotel,

09:31.338 --> 09:33.206
and then
we'll see, okay?

09:33.240 --> 09:35.242
SHAUN: Okay.

09:35.275 --> 09:37.711
**

09:45.653 --> 09:47.921
(BIRDS CHIRPING)

09:50.758 --> 09:52.826
(SIGHS)
How you doing?

09:52.860 --> 09:54.561
I'm ready to go home.

09:58.766 --> 10:03.103
We're not gonna be able
to do that until tomorrow,
so...

10:03.136 --> 10:06.273
Maybe we should try to make
the most of our visit.

10:06.306 --> 10:08.141
(SIGHS)

10:16.149 --> 10:17.951
Shaun, it's okay.

10:17.985 --> 10:19.586
Just because
your dad's dying

10:19.619 --> 10:21.755
doesn't mean he deserves
to be forgiven.

10:23.223 --> 10:26.126
And if he dies
before you're ready
to listen

10:26.159 --> 10:29.129
to whatever
he wants to say,
that's his fault.

10:29.162 --> 10:30.964
His.

10:30.998 --> 10:32.232
Not yours.

10:35.402 --> 10:37.304
There is someone
I'd like to see.

10:38.672 --> 10:40.640
(BIRDS CHIRPING)

10:43.443 --> 10:45.045
LEA: He's in
a peaceful place.

10:45.078 --> 10:47.748
He's decomposed.

10:47.781 --> 10:50.751
Except for maybe
his face and hands.

10:50.784 --> 10:53.553
That's where
they concentrate
the embalming fluid

10:53.586 --> 10:56.389
because that's
what people see
at the funeral.

10:56.423 --> 10:59.292
**

11:00.593 --> 11:02.963
(ROSES THUD)

11:10.537 --> 11:13.640
(SHOVEL SCRAPING,
DIRT CRUMBLING)

11:19.546 --> 11:20.547
Are you ready?

11:25.152 --> 11:26.754
Okay.

11:26.787 --> 11:28.856
Well, you take
as much time as you need.

11:28.889 --> 11:30.523
Your Mom and I
are gonna wait in the car.

11:30.557 --> 11:32.392
I'm not
going with you.

11:34.327 --> 11:35.362
Shaun...

11:35.395 --> 11:36.529
I'm never going
with you.

11:38.966 --> 11:40.968
What are you gonna do?
Hmm?

11:41.001 --> 11:42.602
You gonna live
in that bus?

11:42.635 --> 11:44.104
You gonna eat
out of the trash?

11:44.137 --> 11:46.606
Huh?

11:46.639 --> 11:48.541
Come on, let's go home.
Leave me alone.

11:50.844 --> 11:52.179
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

11:52.212 --> 11:54.915
**

12:08.061 --> 12:09.529
DR. GLASSMAN:
It was an accident, Shaun.

12:10.663 --> 12:12.866
A horrible, tragic accident.

12:14.201 --> 12:15.668
And I know you're hurting.

12:16.837 --> 12:18.839
I promise you,
he's hurting, too.

12:19.439 --> 12:21.842
**

12:26.213 --> 12:28.015
You don't get over
losing a child.

12:33.020 --> 12:34.587
He wants to see you.

12:36.790 --> 12:37.791
What do you
want to do?

12:43.696 --> 12:45.765
But you don't have to.

12:45.799 --> 12:48.268
If you're not ready yet,
that's fine.

12:48.301 --> 12:51.038
Whatever feels right for you,
that's what you should do.

13:03.250 --> 13:05.118
(INSECTS CHIRPING)

13:07.620 --> 13:08.621
Hi, Shaun.

13:11.291 --> 13:12.292
Hello.

13:15.628 --> 13:16.763
Can I hug you?

13:20.100 --> 13:21.234
No.

13:26.306 --> 13:28.541
DR. REZNICK:
Got venous blood return.
I'm in the subclavian.

13:28.575 --> 13:29.642
DR. MELENDEZ: Next step?

13:29.676 --> 13:30.978
Large bore catheter.

13:31.011 --> 13:33.446
(MONITOR BEEPING)

13:35.682 --> 13:37.985
FYI, he grew up poor.

13:38.018 --> 13:40.653
He bought his mom a house
with his signing bonus.

13:40.687 --> 13:43.090
Set up a business
for his brother
and cousins...

13:43.123 --> 13:44.257
Focus on the procedure.

13:44.291 --> 13:45.692
You can write his biography
on your own time.

13:46.960 --> 13:48.962
DR. PARK:
Infusing 400 milliliters
cooling saline.

13:50.063 --> 13:51.764
(MONITOR ALARM BEEPING)

13:54.434 --> 13:56.436
(ALARM STOPS)

13:56.469 --> 13:58.005
Core body temp
down to 94.5.

13:58.038 --> 14:01.408
(ALARM RESUMES)

14:01.441 --> 14:02.475
He's bradycardic.

14:02.509 --> 14:03.676
DR. MELENDEZ:
Push .5 atropine.

14:03.710 --> 14:05.212
Let's get
a transcutaneous
pacer on him.

14:07.280 --> 14:09.349
Low charge.

14:09.382 --> 14:11.518
We can't allow
the contractions to
increase the dislocation

14:11.551 --> 14:12.652
and sever the cord.

14:12.685 --> 14:13.753
CLAIRE: Charge at 40.

14:13.786 --> 14:15.322
(DEFIBRILLATOR WHINES)
40 milliamps.

14:15.355 --> 14:16.689
Clear.

14:16.723 --> 14:17.824
(THUMP)

14:19.392 --> 14:21.328
(FLATLINE)

14:21.361 --> 14:22.595
Can't feel his pulse.

14:22.629 --> 14:24.431
10 milliliters epi
on a long needle.

14:24.464 --> 14:25.632
We should start
compressions.

14:25.665 --> 14:27.100
No, we can't risk
further dislocation.

14:27.134 --> 14:28.601
Should we up the...
No. Keep it at 40.

14:28.635 --> 14:29.802
(DEFIBRILLATOR WHINES)
40 milliamps.

14:29.836 --> 14:31.271
Clear.
(THUMP)

14:31.304 --> 14:34.141
(FLATLINE CONTINUES)

14:34.174 --> 14:36.509
(SIGHS) No response.
Give him more atropine.

14:36.543 --> 14:37.677
DR. REZNICK:
Should we push
more IV epi?

14:37.710 --> 14:38.878
DR. PARK: No,
that'll take too long.

14:38.912 --> 14:40.047
We should increase
the charge by 100.

14:40.080 --> 14:41.314
No, we can't take
that risk.

14:41.348 --> 14:42.415
Better paralyzed
than dead.

14:45.318 --> 14:47.354
(FLATLINE CONTINUES)

14:54.361 --> 14:56.796
(MONITOR BEEPING STEADILY)

14:56.829 --> 14:58.831
He's got a pulse.
(SIGHS)

14:58.865 --> 15:01.001
**

15:03.036 --> 15:05.005
Core temp?
93.2.

15:05.038 --> 15:06.073
That's cool enough.

15:06.106 --> 15:07.607
Let's monitor him closely
overnight,

15:07.640 --> 15:10.177
make sure that his BP
and heart rate are steady
before we start surgery.

15:14.081 --> 15:15.415
(SIGHS)

15:15.448 --> 15:17.684
(INSECTS CHIRPING)

15:23.556 --> 15:25.292
(BREATHES SHALLOWLY)

15:34.034 --> 15:35.368
Shaun, I'm sorry.

15:40.840 --> 15:42.342
It's just...

15:42.375 --> 15:44.077
I always wanted a son.

15:44.111 --> 15:47.747
I mean, a boy
that I could teach
to hunt and fish.

15:50.984 --> 15:52.785
Play catch with.

15:52.819 --> 15:54.321
Have a beer with.

15:56.823 --> 15:59.492
A little kid that
I could carry around
on my shoulders.

16:07.400 --> 16:08.935
And I got angry.

16:10.403 --> 16:12.572
Not at you,
but just me.

16:13.406 --> 16:15.708
I was pissed off
at myself.

16:15.742 --> 16:17.744
Because I couldn't
help my son.

16:19.346 --> 16:21.914
**

16:25.018 --> 16:28.455
No matter
how hard I tried,
I always failed.

16:36.696 --> 16:38.365
But you were
a good kid.

16:45.972 --> 16:48.241
And you've become
a great man.

16:48.275 --> 16:50.009
Better than I could
ever dream of.

16:58.885 --> 17:00.453
I'm proud of you, Shaun.

17:02.322 --> 17:05.392
**

17:19.272 --> 17:20.673
(SNIFFLES)

17:20.707 --> 17:22.175
(VOICE BREAKING)
And I love you.

17:23.843 --> 17:25.845
I just wanted you
to know that.

17:25.878 --> 17:29.316
**

17:29.349 --> 17:31.251
(BREATHES SHAKILY)

17:46.899 --> 17:48.401
You...

17:51.871 --> 17:54.874
...are not
a good person.

18:01.581 --> 18:06.786
You always drank
too much beer,

18:06.819 --> 18:07.920
which made you stink.

18:07.954 --> 18:09.389
Shaun.
Mm.

18:10.290 --> 18:14.894
And you always blame
other people.

18:16.263 --> 18:20.600
And you hit and punch
other people...

18:20.633 --> 18:21.701
Shaun, please calm down.

18:21.734 --> 18:23.770
**

18:30.277 --> 18:32.445
You killed my rabbit.

18:32.479 --> 18:33.880
Shaun...

18:33.913 --> 18:35.948
You killed my rabbit.

18:35.982 --> 18:37.950
And you killed
my brother!

18:39.219 --> 18:41.854
S-So I don't care
that you're dying!

18:41.888 --> 18:43.323
I don't care at all!

18:46.593 --> 18:48.161
(SNIFFLES) Shaun.

18:48.195 --> 18:50.297
(DOOR OPENS)

18:50.330 --> 18:54.567
**

18:54.601 --> 18:55.668
(DOOR SLAMS)

18:59.472 --> 19:00.973
(CELL PHONE CHIMES)

19:03.410 --> 19:05.478
(SIGHS)

19:05.512 --> 19:07.447
(CELL PHONE CLICKING)

19:20.960 --> 19:22.829
You done yet?
We need to
follow up on Art.

19:22.862 --> 19:24.130
I'll be right there.

19:24.163 --> 19:25.632
You said that
ten minutes ago.

19:25.665 --> 19:27.434
I am just finishing up
some charts.

19:27.467 --> 19:28.768
The charts on your phone?

19:30.803 --> 19:31.904
(LIQUID SLOSHES)

19:31.938 --> 19:33.005
Satisfied?

19:34.207 --> 19:37.277
Nice. Very dramatic.
And stupid.

19:37.310 --> 19:38.645
People need to be able
to page you.

19:41.548 --> 19:43.350
(SIGHS)

19:43.383 --> 19:45.151
(DOOR CLOSES)

19:47.620 --> 19:49.956
(TANYA TUCKER'S
THE WINNER'S GAME
PLAYS ON STEREO)

19:49.989 --> 19:52.225
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS)

19:56.229 --> 19:58.265
Tequila, stat.

19:58.298 --> 19:59.399
No, thank you.

20:00.367 --> 20:02.034
* Is a winner's game

20:02.068 --> 20:03.703
(GLASS THUDS)

20:03.736 --> 20:05.538
* No one to thank

20:05.572 --> 20:07.374
We need to do
something fun.

20:08.708 --> 20:11.177
Like go for a swim.

20:11.210 --> 20:13.480
There is a gorgeous lake
a few blocks away.

20:13.513 --> 20:15.114
I saw it
when we first drove in.

20:15.147 --> 20:17.717
It's the Rocky Mountains.
It's December.

20:17.750 --> 20:19.652
So? My family
used to do

20:19.686 --> 20:22.389
a New Year's Eve
"Polar Bear Plunge"
at our lake house.

20:23.189 --> 20:25.392
Sometimes, my dad would...

20:25.425 --> 20:26.893
The diagnosis
is correct.

20:26.926 --> 20:29.562
* ...is just a cause
for sinning

20:29.596 --> 20:31.831
There is no hope.
He's going to die.

20:31.864 --> 20:34.066
* Some see the beginning

20:35.067 --> 20:36.336
Yeah.

20:36.369 --> 20:39.972
* We'd find our way through
the joy and the pain of love

20:40.006 --> 20:41.674
Shaun, I don't think
you're done with your dad.

20:43.576 --> 20:45.845
You can't help him medically,
but you can talk to him.

20:47.013 --> 20:49.382
Yes, you have every right
to be angry,

20:49.416 --> 20:51.250
but I'm not so sure
that's all you feel.

20:52.685 --> 20:54.654
I think we should go home
to the motel,

20:54.687 --> 20:56.255
get some sleep,
wake up in the morning,

20:56.289 --> 20:58.558
go to the Hilltop,
get some pancakes,

20:58.591 --> 21:00.226
and then see
what happens.

21:00.259 --> 21:02.562
* ...is a poor man's drink

21:02.595 --> 21:04.196
Sounds like
a very wise plan.

21:04.230 --> 21:05.598
Good.

21:05.632 --> 21:08.568
On the other hand,
there is that lake.

21:08.601 --> 21:11.103
Oh, my God,
do you ever stop?
No.

21:11.137 --> 21:12.238
I'm going with Lea.

21:13.139 --> 21:15.274
Yes!
The lake is probably
half frozen.

21:15.308 --> 21:17.076
I'm going with Lea.

21:17.109 --> 21:18.878
Let's do this, Shaunie.

21:18.911 --> 21:20.613
(CHUCKLES)

21:20.647 --> 21:22.882
* Is a poor man's drink

21:22.915 --> 21:28.355
* And some say death is just
our cause for sinning *

21:28.388 --> 21:31.924
Your heart is stabilized,
and surgery will likely be
in a few hours.

21:31.958 --> 21:34.927
(INHALES DEEPLY,
EXHALES SHAKILY)

21:34.961 --> 21:37.497
You're gonna walk out of here
and probably even play again.

21:39.999 --> 21:41.834
You want to know
why I chose you guys?

21:44.637 --> 21:47.073
Because I thought
you didn't care
if I played or not.

21:51.110 --> 21:52.945
I hate football.

21:52.979 --> 21:54.180
I always have.

21:57.417 --> 22:00.252
But you've dedicated
your entire life
to being the best at it.

22:01.087 --> 22:05.825
I was 6'1", 250 pounds
in 8th grade.

22:05.858 --> 22:07.093
When I got to high school,
the coach,

22:07.126 --> 22:08.595
he didn't
ask me to play...
He told me.

22:10.196 --> 22:12.131
But from the
first practice, it was...

22:13.099 --> 22:15.001
It's not who I am.

22:15.034 --> 22:17.604
**

22:17.637 --> 22:19.472
(SIGHS)
I wanted to quit, but...

22:22.775 --> 22:25.111
...college coaches
started calling my mom.

22:26.779 --> 22:28.548
She insisted
it was God's plan.

22:29.716 --> 22:30.983
Why else would
I be born this way?

22:33.052 --> 22:35.287
But you're not a kid
anymore.

22:35.321 --> 22:36.623
You must have
plenty of money.

22:37.824 --> 22:39.091
Everybody depend on me...

22:39.125 --> 22:42.529
My mother,
my brother,

22:42.562 --> 22:45.965
my cousins,
my friends.

22:48.234 --> 22:49.469
They'd hate me.

22:52.405 --> 22:53.973
So I prayed to get hurt,

22:54.006 --> 22:56.142
but no matter how
out of control I played...

22:58.545 --> 23:00.079
(SIGHS)

23:01.481 --> 23:02.682
I thought I'd go
to the weight room

23:02.715 --> 23:04.383
and blow out a knee,
and then this happens.

23:05.918 --> 23:08.087
**

23:17.196 --> 23:21.501
He wants closure.
There's no such thing.

23:21.534 --> 23:23.736
Some relationships
are just not meant to be,

23:23.770 --> 23:26.005
which is why people
should focus

23:26.038 --> 23:27.574
on nurturing the ones
they have,

23:27.607 --> 23:30.777
instead of trying to salvage
the ones they've lost.

23:34.280 --> 23:35.347
Talking's done.

23:35.381 --> 23:37.216
Time for action.

23:37.249 --> 23:38.518
Okay.
(LAUGHS)

23:42.354 --> 23:43.355
(EXHALES SHARPLY)

23:46.125 --> 23:47.126
What's wrong?

23:48.628 --> 23:50.497
The majority
of drownings
are caused

23:50.530 --> 23:52.499
by swimming
after drinking alcohol.

23:52.532 --> 23:55.001
Not gonna be a problem,
because we're not gonna swim.

23:55.034 --> 23:56.536
It's way too cold
for that.

23:56.569 --> 23:58.705
We're just gonna run in

23:58.738 --> 24:00.239
until it's deep enough
to dunk our heads

24:00.272 --> 24:01.407
and then run back out.

24:01.974 --> 24:04.110
No.
Oh, come on.

24:04.143 --> 24:05.745
It'll feel amazing.

24:05.778 --> 24:07.880
Like... Like you've just had
an awesome massage.

24:07.914 --> 24:08.981
I don't like massages.

24:09.015 --> 24:10.617
It's not at all
like a massage.

24:10.650 --> 24:12.184
It's... It's not
even close to that.

24:12.218 --> 24:13.786
I don't like the mud.

24:13.820 --> 24:15.722
It gets between my toes.

24:15.755 --> 24:17.056
You won't even feel it.

24:17.089 --> 24:20.026
Your toes will be numb
as soon as they hit the water.

24:20.059 --> 24:21.761
But that feeling
when you get out...

24:21.794 --> 24:24.430
That warm,
tingly sensation...

24:24.463 --> 24:27.466
It's the best high
there is.

24:28.901 --> 24:30.737
That can't be true.

24:30.770 --> 24:32.404
Okay.

24:32.438 --> 24:35.407
Guess I'll just have
to go solo, then.

24:35.441 --> 24:37.276
You're not supposed
to swim alone.

24:37.309 --> 24:38.678
I'm not alone.
You're here.

24:40.079 --> 24:42.114
And you're gonna regret it
if you don't come with me.

24:42.982 --> 24:44.851
(OWL HOOTS)

24:46.986 --> 24:48.020
Suit yourself.

24:52.592 --> 24:53.593
Aah!

25:01.768 --> 25:04.003
(OWL HOOTS)

25:04.036 --> 25:05.204
Lea?

25:08.975 --> 25:10.209
Lea?

25:12.211 --> 25:13.212
Lea!

25:13.846 --> 25:17.016
**

25:24.156 --> 25:26.793
(LAUGHS)
Damn it!

25:26.826 --> 25:29.495
If only I could hold my breath
longer than 15 seconds!

25:32.298 --> 25:34.867
That is not a good joke!

25:34.901 --> 25:36.268
(CHUCKLES)

25:36.302 --> 25:38.370
**

25:41.407 --> 25:42.742
(SIGHS)

25:43.643 --> 25:45.177
(KNOCK ON DOOR)

25:48.881 --> 25:50.583
I knew
you would forgive me.

25:52.919 --> 25:54.621
Shaun's not
an angry person.

25:54.654 --> 25:55.722
Right?

25:55.755 --> 25:58.157
He can be insecure,
maybe.

25:58.190 --> 25:59.626
Uh, stubborn sometimes.

25:59.659 --> 26:01.560
But he's not
an angry person.

26:01.594 --> 26:02.995
And if that's
the last conversation

26:03.029 --> 26:05.164
he has with his dad,
then...

26:05.197 --> 26:06.833
Then all I've succeeded
in doing

26:06.866 --> 26:08.467
is ripping open
an old scab,

26:08.500 --> 26:10.036
and this whole trip
was a mistake.

26:12.171 --> 26:14.573
His dad was a disaster,

26:14.607 --> 26:16.609
and his mom did nothing
to protect him.

26:16.643 --> 26:20.847
So, I just don't think
you need to be so worried

26:20.880 --> 26:22.548
about getting him
to forgive.

26:23.850 --> 26:26.252
**

26:33.292 --> 26:37.163
You're gonna become
a-a parent someday.

26:37.196 --> 26:38.530
Maybe. Right?

26:38.564 --> 26:39.966
I...

26:40.933 --> 26:42.769
Well, if you do,

26:42.802 --> 26:46.939
you're gonna be responsible
for another human being.

26:48.775 --> 26:52.044
And your first job,
number one,

26:54.180 --> 26:55.547
is to keep them alive.

26:56.382 --> 26:58.250
**

27:10.262 --> 27:12.264
You're gonna
make mistakes,

27:12.298 --> 27:15.334
but you hope that one mistake
doesn't scar you for life.

27:17.636 --> 27:19.772
Uh, I'm...

27:19.806 --> 27:21.073
I'm sorry.

27:26.445 --> 27:27.513
(SIGHS)

27:31.150 --> 27:33.319
Shaun's dad needed
a little bit of mercy.

27:41.694 --> 27:43.395
We'll leave
in the morning.

27:43.429 --> 27:44.964
(DOOR CLOSES)

27:45.297 --> 27:48.034
**

27:59.779 --> 28:02.081
(WATER TRICKLING)

28:02.114 --> 28:03.783
I don't like the mud.

28:03.816 --> 28:05.184
It gets between my toes.

28:05.217 --> 28:07.019
Aw, come on, buddy.
We can't turn back now.

28:07.053 --> 28:08.320
We're almost
to the waterfall.

28:09.688 --> 28:11.123
I can wait here.

28:11.157 --> 28:13.325
Um, I-I'll meet you
when you come back.

28:13.359 --> 28:15.261
No, no, no, no,
you're too young
to be left alone.

28:15.294 --> 28:17.163
I tell you what...
I will help you

28:17.196 --> 28:19.631
clean every speck of dirt
off your feet
as soon as we cross.

28:19.665 --> 28:20.900
I don't want to.

28:22.001 --> 28:23.669
(SIGHS)

28:23.702 --> 28:24.837
Okay, well,
what if I carry you?

28:24.871 --> 28:26.005
You won't even touch
the water.

28:26.038 --> 28:27.974
No, I don't want
to be picked up.
It'll be five seconds.

28:28.007 --> 28:31.043
For the most amazing
mountaintop picnic ever!

28:31.077 --> 28:32.478
And I-I got
all your favorite foods.

28:32.511 --> 28:35.347
I got, uh, peanut butter
and jelly on white bread,

28:35.381 --> 28:38.150
I got apples,
chocolate chip cookies.

28:38.184 --> 28:39.385
Huh?

28:40.753 --> 28:42.054
(SIGHS)

28:44.924 --> 28:46.292
Aw, Shaun, come on.

28:46.325 --> 28:48.027
No! No, put me down!
All right, all right,
all right, all right.

28:48.060 --> 28:49.195
No, no, no, buddy,
it's okay, it's okay.

28:49.228 --> 28:50.396
It's okay!
Let me go!
Put me down!

28:50.429 --> 28:51.497
Okay. Okay.
Let me go!

28:51.530 --> 28:52.731
All right, all right.
All right.

28:52.765 --> 28:53.900
You did good.

28:53.933 --> 28:56.202
You're okay.
We're good.
It's all good.

28:56.235 --> 28:57.804
All right,
let's do this.

28:57.837 --> 28:59.839
Put your shoes on,
bud.

28:59.872 --> 29:01.040
(GRUNTS)

29:01.073 --> 29:02.708
(SIGHS)

29:03.876 --> 29:06.712
**

29:20.026 --> 29:22.862
**

29:41.047 --> 29:42.381
These are as good
as I remember.

29:42.414 --> 29:44.416
(BELL DINGS)

29:44.450 --> 29:47.119
(UTENSILS CLACKING,
FOOD SIZZLING)

29:47.153 --> 29:49.555
There's a flight
at 11:00,

29:49.588 --> 29:51.190
if that's what you want.

29:51.223 --> 29:53.559
(DOOR OPENS, BELL JINGLES)

29:53.592 --> 29:55.094
Are you good with that?

29:55.494 --> 29:56.495
Shaun?

29:57.496 --> 29:59.966
You never could get enough
of Hilltop's pancakes.

29:59.999 --> 30:02.268
(ROBO GIRL PLAYS FAINTLY
ON STEREO)

30:02.301 --> 30:05.671
**

30:05.704 --> 30:06.805
Can we talk?

30:07.940 --> 30:09.675
It'll just take a minute.
I promise.

30:12.244 --> 30:13.245
Okay.

30:15.447 --> 30:17.283
(UTENSIL CLACKS)

30:24.490 --> 30:28.094
* When I kiss
her heated lips... *

30:28.127 --> 30:30.762
(MONITOR BEEPING)

30:30.796 --> 30:32.164
Inflammation's
definitely been reduced.

30:32.198 --> 30:33.532
Well done, Doctor.
Thanks.

30:35.734 --> 30:37.403
And get the rods
and place set screws...

30:37.436 --> 30:40.372
Got it.
...while Park and I
compress the spine

30:40.406 --> 30:43.142
above and below the fracture
to improve alignment.

30:43.175 --> 30:45.711
**

30:48.814 --> 30:50.682
All I ever wanted was
to figure out a way

30:50.716 --> 30:52.018
to move past...

30:53.852 --> 30:55.121
Everything.

30:56.488 --> 30:58.124
I wanted us
to be a family again.

31:01.860 --> 31:03.395
Why did you stay
with him?

31:06.198 --> 31:07.533
I don't know.

31:09.969 --> 31:11.370
I just...

31:15.241 --> 31:16.542
I love him.

31:21.147 --> 31:25.484
You loved him
more than me and Steve?

31:25.517 --> 31:26.986
No.

31:27.019 --> 31:29.021
No.

31:29.055 --> 31:31.123
That isn't true.

31:31.157 --> 31:34.460
**

31:34.493 --> 31:35.928
I just...

31:37.363 --> 31:39.498
I guess I knew
what I could do for him.

31:41.133 --> 31:42.868
With you...

31:45.437 --> 31:47.173
I don't blame you
for hating us.

31:48.941 --> 31:50.742
We were young.

31:50.776 --> 31:52.644
Stupid.

31:52.678 --> 31:54.013
Not like people today.

31:55.447 --> 31:57.049
Like Dr. Glassman.

31:59.551 --> 32:02.188
There was so much
we didn't understand
about...

32:05.524 --> 32:07.559
You.

32:07.593 --> 32:09.461
And what you needed
from us.

32:18.870 --> 32:20.439
We've missed you.

32:22.408 --> 32:23.709
So much.

32:30.449 --> 32:32.584
(BREATHES SHARPLY)

32:32.618 --> 32:34.553
Can I hug you?

32:34.586 --> 32:37.123
**

33:09.521 --> 33:12.591
**

33:16.828 --> 33:18.964
(DOOR OPENS, BELL JINGLES)

33:19.665 --> 33:22.434
(DOOR CLOSES)

33:25.671 --> 33:30.576
* That the one
who loves you is waiting

33:30.609 --> 33:34.480
* That the one
who loves you is waiting

33:34.513 --> 33:39.685
* That the one who loves you
is waiting here at home *

33:42.354 --> 33:43.855
I need to talk to my dad.

33:54.633 --> 33:55.967
(INHALES DEEPLY)

34:02.241 --> 34:04.143
I thought you went home.

34:12.584 --> 34:18.857
I couldn't let you put me
on your shoulders.

34:22.328 --> 34:23.995
Or let you hug me.

34:24.029 --> 34:27.032
**

34:31.437 --> 34:35.207
I couldn't make you happy.

34:39.845 --> 34:41.447
You are my son.

34:43.349 --> 34:45.016
You're Shaun.

34:52.258 --> 34:53.559
I forgive you.

35:01.099 --> 35:02.634
And...

35:05.871 --> 35:09.908
...I don't want
to punish you anymore.

35:13.312 --> 35:15.247
I don't want
to punish you.

35:17.816 --> 35:19.951
You're not like
other people.

35:21.387 --> 35:24.089
You're s-so smart.

35:36.235 --> 35:38.204
(BREATHING SHALLOWLY)

35:38.237 --> 35:39.438
But weak.

35:41.039 --> 35:44.310
You're like
a spoiled, little baby.

35:46.111 --> 35:48.180
He's delirious
from the morphine.

35:48.214 --> 35:50.282
You understand.
He... He doesn't know
what he's saying.

35:50.316 --> 35:53.785
You're damn right
Stevie's death
wasn't my fault.

35:53.819 --> 35:56.255
It was yours.
Shh, shh, shh.

35:56.288 --> 35:58.790
He was always trying
to impress you.

35:58.824 --> 36:00.459
You and that
damn rabbit.
Ethan, shh!

36:00.492 --> 36:02.628
DR. GLASSMAN:
Shaun, let's go.
Stop. Shh.

36:02.661 --> 36:04.763
Oh, yeah, go ahead.

36:04.796 --> 36:05.997
Get out of here.

36:06.031 --> 36:08.166
Run away again!
Come on.

36:08.200 --> 36:10.402
G-G-Go ahead!
Run away again!

36:12.304 --> 36:14.506
Shh, shh, shh, shh.
(WHEEZES)

36:14.540 --> 36:16.642
(HORN HONKS IN DISTANCE)

36:16.675 --> 36:18.143
Now what?

36:21.347 --> 36:23.282
You need to tell them.

36:23.315 --> 36:25.951
If they care about you,
they will understand.

36:27.786 --> 36:31.089
No one will blame you
for retiring after
breaking your back.

36:32.658 --> 36:34.593
Nearly paralyzing
yourself.

36:34.626 --> 36:37.128
(SIGHS)

36:37.162 --> 36:39.798
My mom worked
minimum-wage jobs
her whole life.

36:40.866 --> 36:42.601
Raised an entire family
on her own.

36:42.634 --> 36:44.603
And you think
I should tell her
I want to quit the NFL

36:44.636 --> 36:46.505
because I don't
"like" it?

36:46.538 --> 36:48.206
Because it's not "fun"
for me?

36:54.346 --> 36:56.482
You think
I don't understand
what it's like

36:56.515 --> 36:57.983
to need to please
your mother.

36:59.618 --> 37:01.553
No matter
how hard you work,

37:02.688 --> 37:06.525
you still owe
something more.

37:06.558 --> 37:10.729
And every good thing
that has ever happened
to you

37:10.762 --> 37:12.063
is pure luck.

37:15.601 --> 37:18.003
But every bad decision
you make,

37:20.105 --> 37:21.907
that's the real you.

37:21.940 --> 37:24.109
**

37:25.777 --> 37:27.279
And you deserve
to suffer.

37:42.428 --> 37:44.095
(INSECTS CHIRPING)

37:46.732 --> 37:48.233
(KNOCK ON DOOR)

37:57.909 --> 37:59.911
Your mom called.

37:59.945 --> 38:01.947
Your dad passed
30 minutes ago.

38:07.319 --> 38:09.388
(EXHALES SHAKILY)

38:13.459 --> 38:14.960
You want to stay
for the funeral?

38:18.764 --> 38:19.965
No.

38:22.968 --> 38:24.736
I want to go home.

38:27.506 --> 38:28.807
Okay.

38:29.508 --> 38:32.277
(BREATHES SHAKILY)

38:37.449 --> 38:39.951
You want me to stay
for a while?

38:39.985 --> 38:41.086
Talk?

38:42.788 --> 38:44.189
No.

38:47.993 --> 38:50.128
Well, we don't have to talk.
We can just sit.

38:51.963 --> 38:54.265
Or, um, go for a walk.

38:59.137 --> 39:04.543
I'm...tired.

39:08.346 --> 39:09.681
I should go to sleep.

39:13.685 --> 39:14.686
Okay.

39:25.163 --> 39:26.465
Good night.

39:45.851 --> 39:47.252
(SIGHS)

39:48.053 --> 39:50.055
**

39:55.594 --> 39:57.262
(CELL PHONE BEEPS)

39:59.598 --> 40:01.099
Hey, it's Claire.

40:02.501 --> 40:04.670
Yeah, I know.
I, um...

40:04.703 --> 40:07.906
I got a new phone
with a different number.

40:07.939 --> 40:09.608
I changed my mind.

40:12.077 --> 40:14.846
I think we should meet up...
Tonight.

40:22.521 --> 40:23.689
Ma?

40:23.722 --> 40:25.023
Yes, baby.

40:27.192 --> 40:28.259
I'm here.

40:30.929 --> 40:32.598
There's something
I need to tell you.

40:34.633 --> 40:37.268
**

40:53.118 --> 40:55.954
I'm sorry for making
you meet me
after hours like this.

40:55.987 --> 40:57.589
I just...

40:57.623 --> 40:59.057
I really needed someone
to talk to.

40:59.090 --> 41:00.125
Of course, Claire.

41:00.158 --> 41:02.093
I'm always available
for my patients.

41:02.127 --> 41:03.662
Come on in.
Thanks.

41:05.831 --> 41:07.766
(BREATHING SHAKILY)

41:07.799 --> 41:09.935
**

41:16.174 --> 41:18.143
(SNIFFLES)

41:18.176 --> 41:20.411
(SLAPS FOOT)

41:20.445 --> 41:22.247
(SNIFFLING)

41:29.154 --> 41:31.189
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

41:32.524 --> 41:34.025
(KNOCK ON DOOR)
LEA: Shaun?

41:35.527 --> 41:37.763
(KNOCK ON DOOR)

41:37.796 --> 41:39.497
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

41:39.531 --> 41:41.299
**

42:00.518 --> 42:02.554
(BREATHING NORMALIZES)

42:05.657 --> 42:09.160
(CRYING)

42:12.297 --> 42:15.133
**

42:32.217 --> 42:34.720
**
